<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-453-670  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 453 670.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 21 1990 v24 n21 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Taking surgery to a new dimension. (Mayo Clinic neurosurgeonspractice on computer system)(includes related article onComputerworld Smithsonian Awards in the Medicine and Health Carecategory)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harrington, Maura J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Neurosurgeons at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, MN, use a 3Dcomputer graphics system developed by biophysics professor Dr.andO;Richard Robb to perform 'practice' surgery on a computerworkstation using patients' X-ray images.andP;  Three-dimensional imagemodels from magnetic resonance imaging, computerized tomographyand ultrasound are transferred into the workstation, where Robb'sAnalyze program allows over 65 different surgical approaches.andO;Analyze can measure even brain structures and functions throughits 1-mm accuracy.andP;  Surgeons at the Mayo Clinic have used Analyzeto prepare for over 150 operations, finding nothing in the actualpatients that was not shown on the workstation screen.andP;  Analyze isa stand-alone program that runs on most Unix-based workstationsand supports networks.andP;  Four private vendors have licensed theproduct, and over 80 scientists and physicians now use it.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer graphicsMedical DiagnosisImage ProcessingNervous systemSurgeryMayo Clinic.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>